It is not known with certainty how elided syllables were treated in reading. It is probable‚ however, that the vowels and diphthongs were so slurred over as to make them equivalent to y and w, and that when m was cut off it left a nasal sound‚ which was still audible enough to give a nasal character to the syllable.1 Where‚ as in Ecl. i. 13, elision interferes with the main caesura, the line may be'read with‘- out any main caesura, or the sense may be sacrificed to the form of the verse.
